        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We adopt the default correlation configuration for polarization observations in Band 7.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The angular scale of the spiral arm with and spur is ~5 arcseconds in NGC1566, verified using HST imaging. This is well-matched to the usable field-of-view for polarization experiments using ALMA Band 7. Our target synthesised beam (1."4) is well-matched to the typical size of a giant molecular cloud (GMC), and represents a good balance between our science goals and the much greater time investment required for sufficient sensitivity at higher resolution. We note that going to very higher spatial resolution is undesirable since the dust polarisation fraction decreases in parsec-scale GMC substrucures. The dynamic range of spatial scales in our polarisation data will provide enough independent measurements to meet our science goals, including some 'breathing room' to smooth the data if the polarised intensity is lower than we expect. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our target sensitivity is determined by our estimate for the polarised intensity, not the total intensity.

Our estimate for the polarised intensity at 350GHz assumes that the typical dust polarisation fraction will be 10%. This is based on the Planck polarisation results in the Milky Way, which show a median polarisation fraction of 10% for the column densities that we expect in our region. We note that our target galaxy (NGC1566) has a face-on orientation, a geometry that is expected to maximise the magnetic field projected on the plane of the sky, and hence the dust polarization fraction.

For the total intensity, we estimate that structures in our map will have typical 350GHz brightness of 0.8 to 3 mJy per 1.4" beam. This estimate is based on the following procedure. We smoothed and spatially filtered a map of the 500micron (=600GHz) emission in the Large Magellanic Cloud to match the spatial scales that will be present in the proposed ALMA data. We then extrapolated the map to 350GHz, conservatively assuming that a dust emissivity spectral index of 2. Structures in the resulting map that we believe to be representative of the structures that we will detect in NGC1566 (quiescent cold dust condensations and active star-forming regions) had typical flux densities of 10 to 40 mJy for size scales corresponding to our synthesised beam. Accounting for the lower dust-to-gas ratio in the LMC (1/3rd of NGC1566), and the distance of NGC1566 (10Mpc vs 50kpc), we therefore expect typical total 350GHz flux densities of 0.8 to 3 mJy within our synthesised beam. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
