    <prp:abstract>The high angular resolution and superb sensitivity of ALMA enable a previously impossible experiment: tracing the magnetic field structure at cloud scales (~65pc) in the cold gas of a nearby disk galaxy. 

Prior to ALMA, information about the magnetic field in external galaxies has been mostly obtained through polarized radio synchrotron emission. But these data probe the magnetic field in the galactic halo, and not the thin disk of cold, dense gas that fuels star formation. 

Here we propose full polarization observations of the 350GHz dust continuum emission in two fields towards a spiral arm segment and an adjacent interarm spur feature in the nearby grand design spiral galaxy NGC 1566, accessing the magnetic field structure in the cold ISM of a grand-design spiral galaxy for the first time. The data will be used to address fundamental questions that simply cannot be answered by existing datasets:

(i) what is the orientation of the magnetic field relative to cold gas structures?

(ii) how does the magnetic field structure change at the interface of the arm/interarm regions of spiral galaxies? and

(iii) do dust polarization properties vary among star-forming disk galaxies?</prp:abstract>
